The '''Weddell Polynya''', or '''Weddell Sea Polynya''', is a [[polynya]] or irregular area of open water surrounded by sea ice in the [[Weddell Sea]] of the [[Southern Ocean]] off [[Antarctica]] and near the [[Maud Rise]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://efdl.cims.nyu.edu/project_maudness/background/weddell_polynya.html |title=Background - Weddell Polynya |author=David Holland| publisher=New York University |date=5 May 2003 |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Explaining the Weddell Polynya--a large ocean eddy shed at Maud Rise |author=D M Holland |date=1 June 2001 |pmid=11387470 |doi=10.1126/science.1059322 |volume=292 |journal=Science |pages=1697-700}}</ref>
==Occurrences== The size of New Zealand, it re-occurred each winter between 1974 and 1976.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.atmosp.physics.utoronto.ca/ANTARCTIC/weddell_polynya.html| title=The Weddell Polynya |publisher=University of Toronto/NASA |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> These were the first three austral winters observed by the Nimbus-5 Electrically Scanning Microwave Radiometer (ESMR).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nsidc.org/data/docs/daac/nsidc0009_esmr_seaice.gd.html |title=Nimbus-5 ESMR Polar Gridded Sea Ice Concentrations |publisher=National Snow and Ice Data Center |author1=Claire L. Parkinson |author2=Joey C. Comiso |author3=H. Jay Zwally |last-author-amp=yes |date=2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>. From 1976 to 2015 this polynya was rarely observed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nsidc.org/arcticseaicenews/}}</ref> The polynya reoccurred in 2016, and has since appeared in 2017. The 2010s occurrence has been smaller than the 1970s occurrence, being about the size of Maine in 2017, or roughly {{convert|80000|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=ExtremeTech-2017-10-11> {{cite news |url= https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/257295-giant-hole-opens-antarctic-ice-pack-no-one-knows |title= Giant Hole Opens in Antarctic Ice Pack, and No One Knows Why |author= Ryan Whitwam |date= 11 October 2017 |publisher= ExtremeTech }} </ref>
Since the 1970s, the polar Southern Ocean south of the [[Antarctic Circumpolar Current]] has freshened and stratified, likely a result of anthropogenic [[climate change]]. Such stratification may be responsible for suppressing the return of the Weddell Sea polynya.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v4/n4/full/nclimate2132.html |title=Cessation of deep convection in the open Southern Ocean under anthropogenic climate change |publisher= Nature Climate Change |author= Casimir de Lavergne, Jaime B. Palter, Eric D. Galbraith, Raffaele Bernardello & Irina Marinov |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/climate-change-felt-deep-waters-antarctica-180949939/ |title=Climate Change Felt in Deep Waters of Antarctica |author=Sarah Zielinski |publisher=Smithsonian.com |date=3 March 2014 |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>
==Other Antarctic polynyas== The presence of polynyas in [[McMurdo Sound]] provides an ice-free area where penguins can feed, so is important for the survival of the [[Cape Royds]] penguin colony.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz//tm/scholarly/tei-Bio15Tuat03-t1-body-d5.html |title=Penguins in high latitudes |author=B. Stonehouse |series=Tuatara: Volume 15, Issue 3 |publisher=Victoria University of Wellington |date=3 December 1967 |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>
